PART 9: RECOMMENDED SOURCES FOR YOUR TOPIC
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Use credible, authoritative sources. Here are recommended sources for arguing that college is the best post-high school path:

PRIMARY SOURCE 1: Bureau of Labor Statistics - "Education Pays"
URL: www.bls.gov/careeroutlook/2023/data-on-display/education-pays.htm
Data available:
- Median weekly earnings by education level
- Unemployment rates by education level
- Updated annually with current data
Citation name: Bureau of Labor Statistics or BLS

PRIMARY SOURCE 2: Georgetown Center on Education and the Workforce
URL: cew.georgetown.edu
Data available:
- Lifetime earnings by degree type
- Return on investment for college
- Career outcomes by major
- "The College Payoff" report
Citation name: Georgetown Center or Carnevale (Anthony P. Carnevale is the director)

PRIMARY SOURCE 3: Federal Reserve Economic Data
URL: www.newyorkfed.org/research/college-labor-market
Data available:
- Recent graduate employment rates
- Underemployment data
- Earnings premiums over time
Citation name: Federal Reserve Bank of New York

PRIMARY SOURCE 4: National Center for Education Statistics
URL: nces.ed.gov
Data available:
- Employment rates by education
- Earnings data by degree
- Educational attainment statistics
Citation name: National Center for Education Statistics or NCES

SOURCE CREDIBILITY CHECKLIST:
☐ Government source (.gov) or educational institution (.edu)
☐ Author or organization clearly identified
☐ Published within last 5 years
☐ Cites its own sources/methodology
☐ Presents data objectively, not opinion

SOURCES TO AVOID:
✗ Wikipedia (use it for background, not as a source)
✗ Personal blogs
✗ Opinion pieces without data
✗ Sources older than 5-7 years
✗ Sites with clear bias (college marketing, trade school marketing)

